Speakers.

A speaker plays a looping sound from two points on the map at once — a left emitter and a right emitter — so the audio spreads across the space between them like a stereo pair set up in a room. Pick a music track or a source sound, place the two points where you want the sound to come from, and the speaker fills the area with that loop, heard from both sides at the same time. It's the simplest way to lay continuous background music or ambience over a stretch of the map.

How a speaker works.

A speaker takes one looping clip and plays it from both of its points simultaneously, each as a positioned sound the player hears in 3d space. Because the same loop comes from a left point and a right point, the player perceives it spread between the two — set the points at opposite ends of a room and the music seems to fill the whole room; set them close together and it tightens to a single spot. The loop runs continuously for as long as the map is loaded, at the volume and pitch you choose. On 3d maps each point carries its own height.

The clip comes from one of two libraries: the musics library for soundtrack-style pieces, and the sources library for general source sounds. You pick the library first, then the specific clip within it.

Speaker fields.

The speaker form takes the following:

Left position. The left x and left y (and left z on 3d maps) — one of the two points the sound plays from.
Right position. The right x and right y (and right z on 3d maps) — the other point the sound plays from.

Category. Which library the clip comes from: musics for soundtrack pieces, or sources for general source sounds.
Sound (a folder name from the chosen library's list, or none). The looping clip the speaker plays. Pick none for a silent speaker.

Volume. How loud the loop plays, from -100 at the quietest up to 0 at full volume.
Pitch. The playback pitch as a flat value, defaulting to 100 for the clip's natural pitch and ranging from 5 to 1000 — lower values play deeper and slower, higher values brighter and faster.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the sound list, the volume slider, or the pitch slider is focused in the form, press space to start a looping preview of the highlighted clip, and press space again to stop it. Adjusting the volume or pitch slider while the preview is playing updates it live, so you can dial in the level and pitch by ear before placing the speaker.

Authoring speakers by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a speaker is written under the name speaker: speaker lx ly rx ry category sound volume pitch, where lx ly is the left point and rx ry the right point. On 3d maps a left z follows the left y and a right z follows the right y: speaker lx ly lz rx ry rz category sound volume pitch. The category is the literal word musics or sources, the sound must match a folder name in that library or the word none, and the volume and pitch are numbers.
